ggplot(baby, aes(year, n, color = name)) +
  geom_line()

This graph is so chaotic because the frequency of names is included for both males and females for each name. This results in the line graphs going up and down repeatedly since the prevalence of a certain name is much higher for one sex than the other.

Question 2

# Part A
econlong <- pivot_longer(economics,
                         cols = c("pce", "psavert", "uempmed", "unemploy"),
                         names_to = "Outcome",
                         values_to = "Value")

# Part B
econlong2 <- econlong %>%
  filter(Outcome %in% c("psavert", "uempmed"))

ggplot(econlong2, aes(date, Value, color = Outcome)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Economic Outcome", labels = c("Personal Savings Rate", "Mediation Unemployment Duration")) +
  labs(title = "Personal Savings Rate vs Median Duration of Unemployment over Time")

These variables appear to be inversely related in that as the personal savings rate decreases, the median duration of unemployment increases.

Question 3

# Part A
library(Lahman)
data("Teams")
data("People")
data("Batting")
batting <- Batting %>% 
  group_by(playerID) %>% 
  summarize(Home_Run = sum(HR)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(Home_Run))
top30 <- batting %>%
    slice_head(n=30)
top30

# Part B
birthmonth <- People %>%
  select(playerID, birthMonth)
ggbmonth <- left_join(x = top30, y = birthmonth, by = "playerID")

ggplot(ggbmonth, aes(birthMonth)) +
  geom_bar(width = 0.5, fill="blue") + theme_bw() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1:12), labels = c("January", "February", "March", "April", "May", "June", "July", "August", "September", "October", "November", "December"), limits = c(0.5, 12.5)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 0.5)) +
  labs(x = "Birth Month", y = "Count", title = "Frequency of Athletes' Birth Months")

Question 4

slg <- Teams %>%
  filter(yearID >= 1969) %>%
  mutate(X1B = H - (X2B + X3B + HR)) %>%
  mutate(second = X2B*2, third = X3B*3, Home_Runs = HR*4) %>%
  mutate(total_bases = (X1B + second + third + Home_Runs)) %>%
  mutate(SLG = (total_bases/AB)) %>%
  arrange(desc(SLG)) %>%
  select(yearID, teamID, SLG) %>%
  slice_head(n=10)
